label: Immuno
text: Used to evaluate immune system by identifying the specific cells involved in the immune response. Valuable in diagnosis of lymphocytic leukemia lymphoma and immunodeficiency diseases including acquired immunodeficiency syndrome and in the assessment of patient response to chemotherapy and radiation. T and B cell lymphocyte surface markers: ■ Percent T cells (CD2) 60 – 88% ■ Percent helper cells (CD4) 34 – 67% ■ Percent suppressor cells (CD8) 10 – 42% ■ Percent B cells (CD19) 3 – 21%Absolute counts: ■ Lymphocytes 0.66 – 4.60 thou/mL ■ T cells 644 – 2201 cells/mL ■ Helper cells 493 – 1191 cells/mL ■ Suppressor T cells 182 – 785 cells/mL ■ B cells 92 – 392 cells/mL ■ Lymphocyte ratio: TH/TS ratio > 1 T and B cell lymphocyte surface markersT-helper/T-suppressor ratio Present in normal patients and more common as ↑ age. RA: ↑↑ initial titer → ↓prognosis ↑likelihood of being positive the longer pt. has disease Also: Autoimmune disease (e.g. Sjögren’s poly/dermatomyositis SLE scleroderma cryoglobulinemia MCTD) some infections (e.g. bacterial endocarditis osteomyelitis TB syphilis hepatitis EBV) and other disease (e.g. diffuse IPF cirrhosis primary biliary cirrhosis sarcoidosis) Negativeor less than 40 IU/mL Rheumatoid factor These abnormal proteins may be associated with myeloma lymphoma polycythemia vera and SLE. Negative Pyroglobulin test Positive results help diagnose Lyme disease. False positive may occur with high rheumatoid factor titers or syphilis. Positive ELISA confirmed by Western blot test. Negative ≤1:256by indirect fluorescent antibody method; nonreactive by ELISA Lyme disease titer Positive monospot and monotest are presumptive positive EBV IgM and IgG indicate acute and recent or past infection respectively. Negative Infectious mononucleosis tests(monospot monotest heterophileantigen test Epstein-Barr virus (EBV)antiviral capsid antigen IgM and IgG) Positive in hepatitis C infection can be quantitative. Negative Hepatitis C virus RNA Positive in exposure to hepatitis C virus; may indicate acute chronic or cleared infection. Negative Hepatitis C virus antibodies Positive if previous exposure and immunity to hepatitis B. Negative Hepatitis B surface antibody (HBsAb) Positive in acute-stage hepatitis B. Negative Hepatitis B surface antigen (HBsAg) Positive if previous exposure and immunity to hepatitis A. Negative Hepatitis A virus antibodiesIgG (HAVAb/IgG) Positive in acute-stage hepatitis A; develops early in disease. Negative Hepatitis A virus antibodiesIgM (HAVAb/IgM) Differentiation of acute from chronic or old infection. Negative: ≤1:20or ≤1:20 for each individual test Epstein-Barr virus serology (viral capsid antigen IgG and IgM early antigen IgG and nuclear antigen IgG) Positive >1:20 usually indicates acute infection. Repeat specimen in 1–2 weeks for equivocal result. Negative: ≤0:79Equivocal: 0:80 – 1.20 Cytomegalovirus antibodies (CMV IgM) Positive >1:0 unit/mL if exposed to CMV at anytime. Acute and convalescent specimens can help identify acute infection. Negative ≤0.9 units/mL Cytomegalovirus antibodies (CMV IgG) Increase indicates active inflammation. ≤0.8 mg/dL C-reactive protein Increased in mycoplasma pneumonia viral illness mononucleosis multiple myeloma scleroderma. Negative or ≤1:32 Cold agglutinins The repeatedly high incidence of this antigen in cancers of the colon rectum pancreas and stomach suggests that CEA levels may be useful in the therapeutic monitoring of these conditions but it is not a screening test. 0 – 2.5 μg/L (nonsmoker)0 – 5/μg/L (smoker) Carcinoembryonic antigen (CEA) Increased in colon upper gastrointestinal (GI) ovarian and other gynecologic cancers: pregnancy peritonitis. 0 – 35 IU/mL CA 125 Increased in pancreatic hepatobiliary gastric and colorectal cancer gallstones. ≤37 IU/mL CA 19-9 tumor marker Increased in metastatic breast cancer. ≤30 IU/mL CA 15-3 tumor marker Presence and concentration is important in evaluation and treatment of various thyroid disorders such as Hashimoto’s thyroiditis and Graves’ disease. May indicate previous antoimmune disorders. ≤1:100 titer by gelatinor hemagglutination Antithyroglobulin and antimicrosomal antibodies SS-A antibodies are found in Sjögren’s syndrome alone or associated with lupus. SS-B antibodies are associated with primary Sjögren’s syndrome. Negative Anti-SS-A/anti-SS-B antibody Diagnostic of liver and bile duct autoimmune diseases. Negative / 1:20 or less Anti-Smooth Muscle Antibody Highly diagnostic of SLE. Negative Anti-Smith antibody Highly diagnostic for scleroderma. Negative Antiscleroderma antibody Helpful in differential diagnosis of systemic rheumatic disease. Negative Antiribonucleoprotein antibody Helpful in diagnosing chronic gastric disease and differentiating autoimmune pernicious anemia from other megaloblastic anemias. Negative Anti-parietal cell antibody Primary sclerosing cholangitis primary biliary cirrhosis autoimmune hepatitis SLE RA Negative Anti–Neutrophil Atypical (x–ANCA) Strong association: Crescentic glomerulonephritis. Moderate association: Polyarteritis nodosa Churg–Strauss vasculitis. Weak association: Wegener’s granulomatosis. Other possible: Henoch–Schönlein purpura temporal arteritis Negative Anti–Neutrophil Perinuclear (p–ANCA) Reference values apply to all ages. Evaluating patients suspected of having Wegener granulomatosis (WG). May be useful to follow treatment response or to monitor disease activity in patients with myeloperoxidase antibodies. Since it is often impossible to distinguish between WG and other forms of vasculitis on the basis of clinical signs and symptoms tests for PR3 ANCA should be employed with other serologic tests in the initial diagnostic evaluation of patients with clinical features of vasculitis (eg VASC / Antineutrophil Cytoplasmic Antibodies Vasculitis Panel Serum). ≤0.4 U (negative); 0.4-0.9 U (equivocal); >1.0 U (positive) Proteinase 3 Antibodies (PR3) Strong association: Wegener’s granulomatosis Moderate association: Crescentic glomerulonephritis. Weak association: Polyarteritis nodosa Negative Anti–Neutrophil Cytoplasmic (C–ANCA) Increased in SLE chronic hepatitis scleroderma leukemia and mononucleosis. Negative ≤1:40 Antinuclear antibody Helpful in determining the best therapeutic agent in diabetics and the cause of allergic manifestations. Also used to identify insulin resistance. ≤3% binding of labeled beef and pork insulinby patient’s serum; or ≤9 mIU/L Anti-insulin antibody Primarily used in the differential diagnosis of glomerular nephritis induced by antiglomerular basement membrane antibodies from other types of glomerular nephritis. Negative or less than 5εUL Antiglomerular base membrane antibody Valuable in supporting diagnosis or monitoring disease activity and prognosis of systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE). ≤ 70 U by ELISA≤ 1:20 by indirect fluorescence Anti-ds-DNA antibody Considered to be diagnostic for myasthenia gravis in patients with symptoms. Negative or ≤ 0.03 nmol/L Acetylcholine receptor binding antibody Note: Normal value ranges may vary slightly among different laboratories. Immunodiagnostic Test

label: TORCH
text: Titer less 1:16 No previous infection Titer 1:16 – 1:64 Past exposure Titer >1:256 Recent infection Titer >1:1024 Acute infection Toxoplasmosis Antibody Test Negative for IgM and IgG: Susceptive to rubella Positive for IgM: Current or recent rubella infection Positive for IgG: Immunity to rubella Rubella Antibody Test Negative Herpes Simplex Antibody Negative or IgG titer less 1:5: No past infection Cytomegalovirus (CMV) The TORCH test which is sometimes called the TORCH panel consists of tests for antibodies to four organisms that cause congenital infections transmitted from mother to fetus. The name of the test is an acronym for the organisms detected by this panel: Toxoplasma gondii (toxoplasmosis) rubella (German measles) cytomegalovirus (CMV) and herpes simplex virus (HSV). Definition TORCH Panel

label: Diabetes
text: Indication: If two or more values meet or exceed the target level Gestational Diabetes is diagnosed.Note: A 75-gram glucose load may be used although this method is not as well validated as the 100-gram OGTT; the 3-hour sample is not drawn if 75 grams is used. 7.8mmol/L 140mg/dL 3 Hours after load 8.6mmol/L 155mg/dL 2 Hours after load 10.0mmol/L 180mg/dL 1 Hour after load ~ 5.3mmol/L ~ 95mg/dL Fasting (prior to load) Sample drawn after a 100-gram glucose drink (a.k.a. Glucose load) SI Units CU Parameter Gestational Diabetes Diagnostics (OGTT) Note: Some labs use a cutoff 130 mg/dL (7.2 mmol/L) because that identifies 90% of women with gestational diabetes compared to 80% identified using the threshold of 140 mg/dL (7.8 mmol/L). ≥ 7.8mmol/L ≥ 140mg/dL Abnormal needs OGTT ≤ 7.8mmol/L ≤ 140mg/dL Normal screen Sample drawn 1 hour after a 50-gram glucose drink SI Units CU Parameter Gestational Diabetes: Glucose Challenge Test ≥ 11.1mmol/L ≥ 200mg/dL Diabetes 7.8 - 11.1mmol/L 140 - 200mg/dL Impaired (prediabetes) ≤ 7.8mmol/L ≤ 140mg/dL Normal Levels applicable except during pregnancy. Sample drown 2 hours after a 75-gram glucose drink. SI Units CU Parameter Oral Glucose Tolerance Test (OGTT) ≥ 7.0mmol/L ≥ 126mg/dL Diabetes 5.6 - 6.9mmol/L 100 - 125mg/dL Impaired (prediabetes) 3.9 - 5.5mmol/L 70 - 99mg/dL Normal SI Units CU Parameter Fasting Blood Glucose View HgA1c chart Nondiabetic adult: 2.2 – 5 % Diabetic adult: less 7% (ADA guideline) Glycosylated Hemoglobin (Glycated Hgb A1c) 34 – 102μmol/L 10.3 – 0.9mg/dL Pyruvic acid 1.25 – 3g/L 125 – 300mg/dL Phospholipids 500 - 2500 ng./Liter 500 - 2500 pg./mL C-Peptide 43 – 208pmol/L 6 – 29μIU/mL Insulin 1.61 - 2.68mmol/L 170 - 265μmol/L Fructosamine 0.5 – 1.2g/L 50 – 120mg/dL Glycoprotein less 10.0mmol/L less 180mg/dL Glucosepostprandial(with DM) less 7.8mmol/L less 140mg/dL Glucosepostprandial 4.4 - 7.2mmol/L 80 - 130mg/dL Glucose (with Diabetes) 3.9 - 5.5mmol/L 70 - 99mg/dL Glucose fasting 50 – 100ng/L 50 – 100pg/mL Glucagon SI Units CU Parameter Note: Normal value ranges may vary slightly among different laboratories. label: Pleural
text: At least 50% of tuberculous pleural effusions do not involve other organs and are therefore difficult to diagnose. ADA levels >40-60 U/L in the setting of a lymphocytic effusion are specific for TB ≤40U/L - Adenosine Deaminase(ADA) low (≤60 mg/dL)(CPE malignancy hemothorax TB RA SLE Churg-Strauss parasite inf.) same as blood Glucose >500(pancreatitis esophageal rupture and malignancies) - Amylase >10000UL ≤10000UL RBC (erythrocytes) >1000/UL>50% lymphs(TB CA)>50% PMN(inflamm.)>10% Eos(PTX hemothorax drug reaction asbestos parasite inf. Churg-Strauss) ≤1000UL WBC (leukocytes) >3.0 g/dL>0.5 (ratio) ≤3.0 g/dL≤0.5 (ratio) Proteins Fluid|Serum (ratio) >200 IU/dL>0.6 (ratio) ≤200 IU/dL≤0.6 (ratio) LDH Fluid|Serum (ratio) Exudate Transudate Parameter Cloudy thick pleural fluid may indicate the presence of microorganisms and/or white blood cells. claudy Milky appearance may point to lymphatic system involvement. milky Reddish pleural fluid may indicate the presence of blood. reddish Abnormal Exudate Appearance light yellowand clear - Appearance ≤7.3 >7.3 pH >1.016 ≤1.016 Specific gravity Exudate Transudate Parameter Note: Normal value ranges may vary slightly among different laboratories.
